h -- tSun Ra: Eulogy and Light -- tPART THREE MUSIC LIKE DIRT Interviews and Outerviews -- tJohn Cage: The Conversation Game -- tSteve Beresford: M.O.R. and More -- tEvan Parker: Saxophone Botany -- tAnthony Braxton: From Planet to Planet -- tAlton Abraham: Brother's Keeper -- tDerek Bailey: Free Retirement Plan -- tPeter Brotzmann: Machine Gun Etiquette -- tHan Bennink: Swing Softly and Play with a Big Stick -- tThe Ex: Live Free ... Or Try -- tGeorge Clinton: The Hair of the Dog -- tNicolas Collins: Trombipulation -- tJon Rose: The Violable Tradition -- tSun Ra: Gravity and Levity -- tExtending Play: A Guide to Further Listening -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Extended Play, one of the country's most innovative music writers conducts a wide-ranging tour through the outer limits of contemporary music. Over the course of more than twenty-five portraits, interviews, and essays, John Corbett engages artists from lands as distant as Sweden, Siberia, and Saturn. With a special emphasis on African American and European improvisers, the book explores the famous and the little known, from John Cage and George Clinton to Anthony Braxton and Sun Ra. Employing approaches as diverse as the music he celebrates, Corbett illuminates the sound and theory of funk and rap, blues and jazz, contemporary classical, free improvisation, rock, and reggae.Using cultural critique and textual theory, Corbett addresses a broad spectrum of issues, such as the status of recorded music in postmodern culture, the politics of self-censorship, experimentation, and alternativism in the music industry, and the use of metaphors of space and madness in the work of African American musicians. He follows these more theoretically oriented essays with a series of extensive profiles and in-depth interviews that offer contrasting and complementary perspectives on some of the world's most creative musicians and their work. Included here are more than twenty original photographs as well as a meticulously annotated discography. The result is one of the most thoughtful, and most entertaining, investigations of contemporary music available today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAvant-garde (Music). 0aImprovisation (Music). 0aMusicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822379430zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822379430423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822379430.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles